A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
The Republican leaders justify their policy with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, confirming that election fraud in the United States is less than the number of people killed by lightning.
By the way, Republican lawyers reported only 300 cases of electoral fraud in 10 years in the United States.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the vote.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
In contrast to Canada, the US states are responsible for the conduct of the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have announced new laws since 2009 which make the registration procedure difficult.
After the November 2010 elections, this phenomenon has gained in importance, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce the time-limits for early voting, declare the right invalid to register as voters on the day of the election, and refer citizens to the right to vote for which a legal act is available.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no US Member State requested voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the law of Indiana in 2008.
The Republican authorities are hurrying to extend this practice to other States.
Over the last two years, they have been promoting legislation in 34 states that force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible persons, do not possess a photo ID issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a certificate.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the necessary ID card.
Young people, minorities and people with low incomes are disproportionately affected by the new constraints.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with income less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the necessary photo ID.
That's enough.
The students who are regarded as voters, who increase their vote for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who choose more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state called for a proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws calling on voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic votes.
It is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators in 2011 promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on the election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters contributed to the 2004 general elections to register some 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of new voters' registration by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five further states aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida 33% of the voters who chose in advance were African-Americans, although they make up only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who chose in advance.
In contrast, the whites, representing 76% of the voters, represented only 46% of the voters who chose in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote difficult.
The democratic critics advocate the party political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the 2012 decisive states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that those states that have passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral panel to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the vote.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
