At home Victor Gadbois is no day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family meeting in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows, while in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, dies tragically after he has tried everything to survive.
"For six months three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years old," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the home Victor Gadbois come from their residence, 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care to relieve the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the end stage of their life, both at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor Gadbois home and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
Just this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care face the adoption of a law regulating death assistance and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has a right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was 14 days of great pain in the emergency room without taking measures to relieve them.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologens treat their patients with fades to the last day, despite the worst predictions.
The chances of survival of Hélène Richard were minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she regrets that I quit the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff that it has not allowed this request after their pains have been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care during pain treatment is not omnipotent.
According to Elsie Monereau, Head of Palliative Care of the Society of Home Palliative Care of the Montreal metropolitan area, 8% of patients do not speak of pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which requires either sporadic or permanent intervention of the patient up to the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will be more and more likely to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pains are not eased all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased".
