After the price of Bitcoin reached a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, he fell five months later to 2 dollars before he recovered on about ten dollars today (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to the conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits" used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes even switch back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is monitored and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously accountants, auditors, money issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures the anonymity.
A series of related data transactions is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
The content of the file also makes it possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public accounts, which are distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a crucible of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computer "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "cracked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can effortlessly check if it is the right number.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unconnected, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundred million pieces, leaving a certain margin of play...
In addition, the difficulty of the task with any improvement of the computing power is increased.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The sites that provide Bitcoin services were attacked and the bitcoin deposits stolen.
"The used vulnerability does not concern the actual protocol," says Pierre Noyzat, who just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the invoice and showed that almost 80% of the bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "Mega Locks Sale" was launched.
"Three thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noyzat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are thus cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Nouzat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
It is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are reviewed in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time until bitcoin gets through, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicted.
By the way, in its report, the ECB envisages re-evaluation of the various risks, today considered to be high, in the event of the success of this currency.
