In November 1979, a mob of demonstrative Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they demanded the delivery of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the USA after the revolution, who had preserved the patronage over his regime for decades.
For the American government there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have seriously damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt of the liberation of the hostages only made everything worse.
After 444 days of negotiations by the Algerian Government, the diplomats arrested were finally released.
The fate of the hostages called out at home a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the US a small victory.
Six ambassadors immediately managed to flee from the occupation of the message.
This ended after many complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports barred as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also made the collaboration of Hollywood necessary.
To make the tarnung credible, article about this film project appeared in specialist journals, there were press conferences held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time, and the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic politthriller, but also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful housekeeper's piece, such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on one side the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironically and easily overstretched, are coming.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA Central and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the halls, on the telephone...
Ben Affleck has achieved a remarkable relaunch of his career with this film.
From a smiled actor has become a respectable director, and also as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Crimea No children's play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without mercy (2010).
At the same time it is Affleck's first film that does not play in the home Boston director's Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics of the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
But Afleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entrance sequence of the embassies is very impressive in their clarity, and nevertheless conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck has a similar effect with his team also on fictional scenes (the false film staff on a bass player in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that history does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality a little - which then doesn't always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is turned away from a telephone call in America, or also the persecution hunt on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its all too wide spread, which is required by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their figures would have earned more space, and therefore they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film thereby loses a bit of traction. It is a film that can be followed with a certain interest and the design and retro style of a thriller from the 70th year.
However, it is difficult to inspire enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history living to this day in a certain way and as proof of how the notions of the almighty and all-knowing intelligence are, it is sufficient.
