Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians in the United Nations.
But then Berlin was evaded.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about setting up a flight ban zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that's right.
That is because it is precisely transforming its foreign policy and away from a policy that was so to speak managed by the United States, towards a German foreign policy.
It is a challenge that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
The Germans thus find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still pressing for their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy as they have France or Great Britain.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions with national interests, which are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the attitude of the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to confront the public, but also the elite, in the Arab countries.
It certainly plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to attach too much weight to it either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining in important decisions, for example in voting on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
Therefore, I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect.
It signals that as an international player it must be taken seriously and its interests must be considered.
There are various opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government has quite an understanding of the European position in secret.
But due to the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as big as they always appear.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so half-witted by Netanyahu's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand, and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not at present the case.
So they can't be part of a wider line and have to push things out of their own position instead.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of the relationship with Israel.
That's always been a sensitive topic.
But I think the Germans are aware that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany itself see itself in the role of an important international player - does Germany want to play a leading role at all?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany assumes a greater role, different anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be receptive to various neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European policy is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is there?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
