Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The world trowel of the basketball, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been connected to basket sports for more than 60 years and has traveled the whole world.
Few in Puerto Rico have as large a spiritual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for six years, whether as players of lower classes, players of the first national league, proxy and head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or President of the Basketball Association.
"For my life I set up a lot of hats in basketball, even several at the same time when I was president of the BSN, head of the national team and president of the Federation in the 1990s," Reyes remembered when visiting Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those who remember at his time at the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years that I enjoyed most, because since 1967 I was allowed to be part of eight of the Vaqueros Championships as managing director, co-manager or trainer.
There were many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I passed with a championship 1981, the year of the debut of Jerome Mincy at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good administrator," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said: "I have a very strong and 2 m big player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players that Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended the freelance specialist Raymond Gousse, who had become a citizen and was one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had enabled a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would take care of another one.
The Vaqueros Championship with Gausse was granted to him, but already out of a distance because he was already at the top of the Federation in 1988.
At that time he intended to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we won for the first time at the previous Olympic tournament in Mexico against the USA.
Then came the 1990 World Championship, where we occupied the fourth place, which should have been bronze, if not this Canadian referee who had let us repeat the last move for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is among the best, as well as those who won the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is the team of the 1991 pan-American games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the team of the USA a battle, as at the time, when they won against us at the bronze World Championship.
At that team not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and Piculin (Ortiz), but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there for a knee injury in 1990.
A team that maybe wasn't the best in terms of personalities, but with whom we won a gold medal and which brought us great joy was that of the 1995 pre-olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitin as a substitute for the locked players because of the incidents on the Pan American games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against any forecast.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was no doubt Piculin Ortiz.
His figures at the level of the international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as Piculin.
And this, without taking into account his career in the different leagues in which he played.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
This is a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like Leo Arill's work.
What do you think is the best thing you've achieved in the Federation?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN at the beginning of the 1990s up to 17 teams in one season.
What else are you doing?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalisation of the lower categories.
That the boys in Ponce, for example, only play in their territory and first meet in the national playoffs on teams from other corners of the island.
Today the children make unnecessary many trips and games.
At least I see the result of the required trainings and courses for trainers, table officers and arbitrators.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to hear music, watch videos of music of my time in YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always with me.
Larry Hagman is dead
Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas) and became famous worldwide with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas", where he played a scrupulous, hideous and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the J.R. Ewing oil magnate in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 80s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who came back this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died on Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved birthplace Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role that most liked him," said the family.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebrations of the harvest Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, said her publicist Jeffrey Lane.
